# Docker + Infrastructure Rules

## Dockerfile
- Always specify a non-root user before CMD:
  ```dockerfile
  RUN adduser --disabled-password --gecos "" appuser
  USER appuser
  ```
- Add HEALTHCHECK on the web service:
  ```dockerfile
  HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=10s --start-period=5s --retries=3 \
    CMD curl -f http://localhost:8000/health || exit 1
  ```
- Layer cache order: `COPY requirements.txt` → `RUN pip install` → `COPY . .` (source last)
- Combine RUN commands with `&&` to minimize layers
- Never add secrets in `ENV` instructions — use `env_file` in docker-compose at runtime
  > WHY: Non-root + HEALTHCHECK are the minimum production-readiness bar. Root processes in containers are a containment escape risk.

## .dockerignore
Always maintain a `.dockerignore` that excludes:
```
.git
.env
.venv
venv
__pycache__
*.pyc
.pytest_cache
*.egg-info
```
> WHY: Without .dockerignore, the build context sends your entire git history and local secrets to the Docker daemon.

## docker-compose.yml
- `env_file: .env` at runtime — never bake secrets into the image
- `depends_on` for service startup order
- Mount source as volume only in development — remove in production builds
- Redis service: use `redis:alpine` (minimal attack surface)
  > WHY: Volume mounts in production containers allow host filesystem access.

## PostgreSQL / Supabase SQL
- Use `TIMESTAMPTZ` not `TIMESTAMP` for all datetime columns
  > WHY: `TIMESTAMP` stores local time without timezone — ambiguous across DST transitions and server migrations.
- Always add `NOT NULL` constraints where nullable values are not intentional
- Index all columns used in `WHERE`, `JOIN`, and `ORDER BY` clauses
- Use `UNIQUE(name, item)` constraints at the DB layer — not just application layer
- Migrations must be non-destructive: add columns with defaults, never drop without a rollback plan
- All mutations go through parameterized RPC functions — never raw string interpolation
  > WHY: DB-level constraints are the last line of defense. Application-layer validation can be bypassed; DB constraints cannot.

## Supabase RPC Contract
The `decrement_inventory` RPC is the only mutation path for inventory. Its signature:
```sql
decrement_inventory(p_name TEXT, p_item TEXT, p_qty INTEGER) RETURNS SETOF hospital_inventory
```
- Called as: `supabase.rpc("decrement_inventory", {"p_name": ..., "p_item": ..., "p_qty": ...})`
- Empty `response.data` = 0 rows updated = insufficient stock → return `False`
- Never replicate this logic in Python
  > WHY: The Postgres row-lock in the RPC is the only concurrency-safe path. Python-side logic has a TOCTOU race.
